Following the <tag name="DATE" value="start"/>11 September 2001<tag name="DATE" value="end"/> attacks, <tag name="PERSON" value="start"/>Kwa[niewski<tag name="PERSON" value="end"/>organized an international conference in <tag name="LOCATION" value="start"/>Warsaw<tag name="LOCATION" value="end"/>, with participation of leaders from Central, Eastern and <tag name="LOCATION" value="start"/>South-Eastern Europe<tag name="LOCATION" value="end"/>to strengthen regional activities in fighting international terrorism. Under <tag name="PERSON" value="start"/>Kwa[niewski<tag name="PERSON" value="end"/>'s leadership, <tag name="ORGANIZATION" value="start"/>Poland<tag name="ORGANIZATION" value="end"/>became a strong ally of the <tag name="ORGANIZATION" value="start"/><tag name="ORGANIZATION" value="start"/>United States<tag name="ORGANIZATION" value="end"/><tag name="ORGANIZATION" value="end"/>in the war on terror, and contributed troops in the <tag name="ORGANIZATION" value="start"/>Iraq<tag name="ORGANIZATION" value="end"/>war, a move that was highly controversial in <tag name="ORGANIZATION" value="start"/>Poland<tag name="ORGANIZATION" value="end"/>and <tag name="LOCATION" value="start"/>Europe<tag name="LOCATION" value="end"/>. <tag name="ORGANIZATION" value="start"/>Poland<tag name="ORGANIZATION" value="end"/>was in charge of a sector of Iraq after the removal of <tag name="PERSON" value="start"/>Saddam Hussein<tag name="PERSON" value="end"/>.
